Now we have two critical pieces of information:

**1. The new image IS deployed** — the deployment shows `dev-010848cb` which is your latest build.

**2. Two different errors now** — this is the key insight:
- `NoSuchFieldError: READ_UNKNOWN_ENUM_VALUES_USING_DEFAULT_VALUE` — line 235 (new databind code ✅)
- `NoSuchMethodError: 'java.lang.String com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonProperty.namespace()'`

The second error is **new and different**. `JsonProperty.namespace()` was added in jackson-annotations **2.12**. This means somewhere a **pre-2.12 `jackson-annotations` class is still being loaded at runtime** — even though your jar has `2.17.2`.

This confirms our earlier suspicion: **one of your vendored utility jars (`SBINEWPG_2023`, `PGPUtility`, `BASE64DecoderData`, or one of the `sbi_*` jars) has old Jackson annotation classes physically shaded inside it.**

The `resolutionStrategy` in `build.gradle` controls which **standalone jar files** Gradle puts in `BOOT-INF/lib/`. It cannot strip classes that are **compiled inside** a vendor jar.

## Prove it right now from the pod

```bash
oc exec -it payment-paymentservice-d746cdb85-8rv7x -n dev-transaction -- \
  sh -c 'find /app -name "*.jar" 2>/dev/null; ls /'
```

This tells us where the jar sits and what the container filesystem looks like. Then:

```bash
oc exec -it payment-paymentservice-d746cdb85-8rv7x -n dev-transaction -- \
  sh -c 'cd /tmp && cp /app/epay_payment_service-*.jar app.jar && jar tf app.jar | grep -i "JsonProperty\|JsonFormat\|jackson/annotation" | head -30'
```

If `jar` is not available:

```bash
oc exec -it payment-paymentservice-d746cdb85-8rv7x -n dev-transaction -- \
  sh -c 'cd /tmp && cp /app/epay_payment_service-*.jar app.jar && python3 -c "
import zipfile, sys
with zipfile.ZipFile(\"app.jar\") as z:
    entries = [e for e in z.namelist() if \"jackson/annotation\" in e.lower() or \"JsonProperty\" in e or \"JsonFormat\" in e]
    for e in entries:
        print(e)
        if e.endswith(\".jar\"):
            with z.open(e) as inner_bytes:
                import io
                inner_zip = zipfile.ZipFile(io.BytesIO(inner_bytes.read()))
                for ie in inner_zip.namelist():
                    if \"jackson\" in ie.lower():
                        print(\"  --> \" + ie)
"'
```

This will show us exactly which nested jar inside `BOOT-INF/lib/` contains the old `jackson-annotations` classes.

## While that runs — the fix direction

Once we identify the culprit jar (almost certainly `SBINEWPG_2023.jar` or one of the SBI utility jars), the fix in `build.gradle` is to add a `bootJar` task that strips the shaded Jackson classes from that jar before packaging:

```gradle
bootJar {
    // Strip shaded jackson-annotations classes from vendor jars
    // that bundle old versions internally
    requiresUnpack('**/SBINEWPG_2023.jar')
}
```

But first run the Python check above and paste which jars come back with `jackson/annotation` entries inside them. That will tell us exactly which jar(s) to target.
